{"title_page": "Whatipu", "text_new": "[[Image:Whatipu.jpg|thumb|right|Whatipu beach.]]\n[[Image:Karekare1.jpg|thumb|right|Looking south toward Whatipu.]]\n[[Image:Piha2.jpg|thumb|right|Looking South over Karekare to the Manukau Heads.]]\n[[File:Whatipu Beach And Manukau Heads.jpg|thumb|right|Whatipu from the air, looking east.]]\n\n'''Whatipu''' is a remote [[beach]] on the west coast of the [[Auckland Region]] in the [[North Island]] of [[New Zealand]]. The Whatipu area has been managed as a scientific reserve by the Auckland Regional Council since 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piha.co.nz/whatipu-scientific-reserve/|title=Whatipu Scientific Reserve|access-date=20 March 2016}}</ref> The road to it is unsealed. To the south of Whatipu is [[Manukau Harbour]]. To the north is [[Karekare, New Zealand|Karekare]]. Whatipu is located at the southern end of the Wait\u0101kere Ranges. Shifting sands have substantially changed the beach since the 1940s. Over 6 square kilometres has been added to the beach since then{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}.\n\n== Water ==\nWhatipu does not have a surf patrol. Swimming may not be safe due to [[Rip current|rips]], in common with all beaches west of Auckland. [[HMS Orpheus (1861)|HMS ''Orpheus'']] ran aground just inside the Manukau Harbour entrance south of Whatipu in 1863 with the loss of 189 lives. It was the biggest shipping disaster in New Zealand history.<ref name=\"GhostHunt\">{{cite book|author1=Julie Miller|author2=Grant Osborn|title=Ghost Hunt: True New Zealand Ghost Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YDO9AAAACAAJ|accessdate=15 December 2011|date=October 2005|publisher=Penguin Group New Zealand, Limited|isbn=978-0-7900-1012-0|page=}}</ref>\n\n==Caves==\nThere are caves about 20 minutes walk from the carpark, but there is no access from the caves to the beach. In pre-European times, the caves were used as shelter by travellers. In the early 20th century, the largest cave was used for dances, but sand has since drifted into the cave and the dance floor is now covered by five metres of sand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasons.co.nz/auckland/auckland-beaches|title=Auckland Beaches |publisher=[[Jasons Travel Media]]}}</ref> During the timber mill era, the larger caves were also a popular venue for meetings for mill workers.<ref>[http://www.theaucklander.co.nz/news/best-auckland-parks/1217377/  7 super Auckland parks to visit this summer] Retrieved January 2012</ref>\n\n==Historic Industry==\nA timber mill was built at Whatipu in 1867 to service the [[Agathis australis|kauri]] trade. A tramline was built to a second timber mill three kilometers north in 1870, and eventually extended up to [[Piha]] and [[Anawhata]]. The mills closed in 1886 when the kauri ran out.\n\n==Whatipu-Gibbons Track & Kura-Omanawanui Tracks==\nAt 6-hours return, the route for this track begins at the carpark at Whatipu. It leads up the hill to the right of the carpark and is clearly marked.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} It follows the top of the cliffs to the Pararaha Valley where it descends to the beach at Pararaha point. It then follows the beach back to Whatipu. Paratutae Rock at the harbour entrance is difficult and particularly dangerous to climb down.<ref>Day Walks of Greater Auckland, Marios Gavalas and Peter Jansson, Page 68. Reed Publishing 2003</ref> The Kura-Omanawanui Tracks are the other notable walk out of Whatipu.   Follows Kura Track eastwards alongside the stream through bush, then climbs steeply to Puriri Ridge and the Whatipu Road.  Back via Omanawanui Track, a switchback ridge in open bush with views across the Manukau Harbour and the Whatipu valley to the west coast.   Time 4 hours.<ref>Walking the Wait\u0101kere Ranges, Alison Dench & Lee-Ann Parore, p.150</ref>\n\n== Modern history and in the media ==\nIn 2005, the remains of a man who had been missing for four years were found by police at Whatipu's Destruction Gully. It was speculated that the man was the victim of an accident during fishing on the Manukau Harbour.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/accidents/news/article.cfm?c_id=13&objectid=10007698 Whatipu remains end four-year search for missing man Retrieved January 2012]</ref> In 2006, the location was featured on [[Ghost Hunt (NZ TV series)|Ghost Hunt]], a New Zealand paranormal television show.<ref>{{cite web|author=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/ghost-hunt-nz/abandoned-psychiatric-hospital-1342534/ |title=Ghost Hunt (NZ): Abandoned Psychiatric Hospital |publisher=CBS Entertainment |date= |accessdate=2011-12-15}}</ref> In the 21st century, Whatipu has been used for the Wild Turkey Off-Road Half Marathon/15&nbsp;km.<ref>[http://events.stuff.co.nz/2012/wild-turkey-off-road-half-marathon-15km/auckland Auckland - stuff.co.nz Wild Turkey Off-Road Half Marathon/15km \u2013 Auckland \u2013 stuff.co.nz] Retrieved January 2012</ref> The Whatipu Beach Beacon is a [[lighthouse]] of the area.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=10778527 Leading lights in New Zealand \u2013 Life & Style \u2013 NZ Herald News] Retrieved January 2012</ref>\n\n{{coord|37|01|48|S|174|28|48|E|region:NZ_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/collection/photos/search/searchterm/Whatipu/field/title/ Photographs of Whatipu] held in [[Auckland Libraries|Auckland Libraries']] heritage collections.\n\n[[Category:Beaches of the Auckland Region]]\n[[Category:Reportedly haunted locations in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Whatipu.jpg|thumb|right|Whatipu beach.]]\n[[Image:Karekare1.jpg|thumb|right|Looking south toward Whatipu.]]\n[[Image:Piha2.jpg|thumb|right|Looking South over Karekare to the Manukau Heads.]]\n[[File:Whatipu Beach And Manukau Heads.jpg|thumb|right|Whatipu from the air, looking east.]]\n\n'''Whatipu''' is a remote [[beach]] on the west coast of the [[Auckland Region]] in the [[North Island]] of [[New Zealand]]. The Whatipu area has been managed as a scientific reserve by the Auckland Regional Council since 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piha.co.nz/whatipu-scientific-reserve/|title=Whatipu Scientific Reserve|access-date=20 March 2016}}</ref> The road to it is unsealed. To the south of Whatipu is [[Manukau Harbour]]. To the north is [[Karekare, New Zealand|Karekare]]. Whatipu is located at the southern end of the Wait\u0101kere Ranges. Shifting sands have substantially changed the beach since the 1940s. Over 6 square kilometres has been added to the beach since then{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}.\n\n== Water ==\nWhatipu does not have a surf patrol. Swimming may not be safe due to [[Rip current|rips]], in common with all beaches west of Auckland. [[HMS Orpheus (1861)|HMS ''Orpheus'']] ran aground just inside the Manukau Harbour entrance south of Whatipu in 1863 with the loss of 189 lives. It was the biggest shipping disaster in New Zealand history.<ref name=\"GhostHunt\">{{cite book|author1=Julie Miller|author2=Grant Osborn|title=Ghost Hunt: True New Zealand Ghost Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YDO9AAAACAAJ|accessdate=15 December 2011|date=October 2005|publisher=Penguin Group New Zealand, Limited|isbn=978-0-7900-1012-0|page=}}</ref>\n\n==Caves==\nThere are caves about 20 minutes walk from the carpark, but there is no access from the caves to the beach. In pre-European times, the caves were used as shelter by travellers. In the early 20th century, the largest cave was used for dances, but sand has since drifted into the cave and the dance floor is now covered by five metres of sand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasons.co.nz/auckland/auckland-beaches|title=Auckland Beaches |publisher=[[Jasons Travel Media]]}}</ref> During the timber mill era, the larger caves were also a popular venue for meetings for mill workers.<ref>[http://www.theaucklander.co.nz/news/best-auckland-parks/1217377/  7 super Auckland parks to visit this summer] Retrieved January 2012</ref>\n\n==Historic Industry==\nA timber mill was built at Whatipu in 1867 to service the [[Agathis australis|kauri]] trade. A tramline was built to a second timber mill three kilometers north in 1870, and eventually extended up to [[Piha]] and [[Anawhata]]. The mills closed in 1886 when the kauri ran out.\n\n==Whatipu-Gibbons Track & Kura-Omanawanui Tracks==\nAt 6-hours return, the route for this track begins at the carpark at Whatipu. It leads up the hill to the right of the carpark and is clearly marked.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} It follows the top of the cliffs to the Pararaha Valley where it descends to the beach at Pararaha point. It then follows the beach back to Whatipu. Paratutae Rock at the harbour entrance is difficult and particularly dangerous to climb down.<ref>Day Walks of Greater Auckland, Marios Gavalas and Peter Jansson, Page 68. Reed Publishing 2003</ref> The Kura-Omanawanui Tracks are the other notable walk out of Whatipu.   Follows Kura Track eastwards alongside the stream through bush, then climbs steeply to Puriri Ridge and the Whatipu Road.  Back via Omanawanui Track, a switchback ridge in open bush with views across the Manukau Harbour and the Whatipu valley to the west coast.   Time 4 hours.<ref>Walking the Wait\u0101kere Ranges, Alison Dench & Lee-Ann Parore, p.150</ref>\n\n== Modern history and in the media ==\nIn 2005, the remains of a man who had been missing for four years were found by police at Whatipu's Destruction Gully. It was speculated that the man was the victim of an accident during fishing on the Manukau Harbour.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/accidents/news/article.cfm?c_id=13&objectid=10007698 Whatipu remains end four-year search for missing man Retrieved January 2012]</ref> In 2006, the location was featured on [[Ghost Hunt (NZ TV series)|Ghost Hunt]], a New Zealand paranormal television show.<ref>{{cite web|author=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/ghost-hunt-nz/abandoned-psychiatric-hospital-1342534/ |title=Ghost Hunt (NZ): Abandoned Psychiatric Hospital |publisher=CBS Entertainment |date= |accessdate=2011-12-15}}</ref> In the 21st century, Whatipu has been used for the Wild Turkey Off-Road Half Marathon/15&nbsp;km.<ref>[http://events.stuff.co.nz/2012/wild-turkey-off-road-half-marathon-15km/auckland Auckland - stuff.co.nz Wild Turkey Off-Road Half Marathon/15km \u2013 Auckland \u2013 stuff.co.nz] Retrieved January 2012</ref> The Whatipu Beach Beacon is a [[lighthouse]] of the area.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=10778527 Leading lights in New Zealand \u2013 Life & Style \u2013 NZ Herald News] Retrieved January 2012</ref>\n\n{{coord|37|01|48|S|174|28|48|E|region:NZ_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/?p=q&collection=p20062coll1&search=whatipu&field=title&mode=all&conn= Photographs of Whatipu] held in [[Auckland Libraries|Auckland Libraries']] heritage collections.\n\n[[Category:Beaches of the Auckland Region]]\n[[Category:Reportedly haunted locations in New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Agh47", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:updated photographs link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whatipu"}
{"title_page": "Outline of space exploration", "text_new": "{{Short description|1=Overview of and topical guide to space exploration}}\n<!--... Attention:  THIS IS AN OUTLINE\n\n        part of the set of 740+ outlines listed at\n             [[Portal:Contents/Outlines]].\n\n                 Wikipedia outlines are\n              a special type of list article.\n              They make up one of Wikipedia's\n                content navigation systems\n\n                See [[Wikipedia:Outlines]]\n                      for more details.\n                   Further improvements\n              to this outline are on the way\n...-->\n[[Image:S122e008264.jpg|thumb|250px|The [[European Space Agency]]'s [[Columbus Module]] at the [[International Space Station]], launched into space on the U.S. Space Shuttle mission [[STS-122]] in 2008.]]\n\nThe following [[Outline (list)|outline]] is provided as an overview of and topical guide to space exploration:\n\n'''[[Space exploration]]''' &ndash; use of [[astronomy]] and [[space technology]] to explore [[outer space]].<ref>\n{{cite web | url = http://adc.gsfc.nasa.gov/adc/education/space_ex/exploration.html | title = How Space is Explored | publisher = NASA | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090702153058/http://adc.gsfc.nasa.gov/adc/education/space_ex/exploration.html | archivedate = 2009-07-02 }}</ref> Physical [[exploration]] of space is conducted both by [[human spaceflight]]s and by [[robotic spacecraft]].\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n== Essence of space exploration ==\n\n[[Space exploration]]\n* [[Big Science]]\n* [[Exploration]]\n* [[High tech]]\n* [[Outer space|Space]]\n* [[Human spaceflight|Spaceflight]]\n\n== Branches of space exploration ==\n\n* [[Human spaceflight]]\n* [[Spaceflight#Uncrewed|Uncrewed spaceflight]]\n\n== History of space exploration ==\n{{Main|Space exploration#History{{!}}History of space exploration|Timeline of space exploration}}\n* [[Remote sensing|Remote sensing of Earth]]